<methodology slug="cog-walk-basics">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ux-researcher</domain>
    <summary>A usability inspection method where evaluators step through a task from a first-time user's perspective, answering four questions per step about motivation, visibility, mental models, and feedback.</summary>
    <category>evaluation</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>cognitive-walkthrough</tag>
      <tag>usability-inspection</tag>
      <tag>learnability</tag>
      <tag>first-time-user</tag>
      <tag>evaluation</tag>
    </tags>
    <applies-to>both</applies-to>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Cognitive Walkthrough: Basics</title>

    <summary>A usability inspection method where evaluators step through a task from a first-time user's perspective, answering four questions per step: (1) Will the user try to achieve the right effect? (2) Will they notice the correct action? (3) Will they associate the action with the desired effect? (4) Will they see that progress is being made? Designed specifically to expose learnability failures before user testing.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Onboarding failures and first-use drop-off occur because teams evaluate their own interfaces as experts, not as first-time users. The four-question framework forces evaluators to separate motivation, visibility, labeling, and feedback — four distinct mechanisms that fail independently. It is cheap (no participants needed), fast, and works on prototypes before any code ships.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-launch usability inspection of an onboarding flow, signup, or first-run experience where no users are available yet.</item>
        <item>Evaluating clickable prototypes (Figma, Framer, deployed staging) for learnability before investing in moderated usability testing.</item>
        <item>Reviewing AI-generated UI from a design-to-code tool against the four-question framework before merging to main.</item>
        <item>Onboarding-flow regressions in CI: a vision-capable agent walks the latest preview build and flags new Q1/Q2/Q3/Q4 failures.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Expert-user efficiency tasks (power-user shortcuts, dashboards). Use heuristic evaluation or quantitative testing.</item>
        <item>Highly subjective aesthetic decisions; the four questions don't catch visual hierarchy issues well.</item>
        <item>When you have real users available — actual usability testing always beats inspection.</item>
        <item>Static brand/marketing pages with no task flow — there are no "steps" to walk through.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="the-four-questions">
      <rule>
        <statement>Answer all four questions for every step in the action sequence. Do not skip any step, including steps the team considers "obvious". The most useful findings are often on steps the team assumed were trivial.</statement>
        <rationale>Expert familiarity with the interface causes teams to skip steps that new users routinely fail on. Systematically skipping "obvious" steps is how critical learnability failures survive to production.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Q1: Will the user try to achieve the right effect? Checks whether the goal is clear, action is needed, and motivation is present.</statement>
        <rationale>Users often do not know they are supposed to do something. If the task goal is not communicated, the user will not attempt the correct action regardless of how visible or labeled it is. Common failures: user does not know something is required at this step; user thinks they are done when they are not (premature success perception).</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Q2: Will the user notice the correct action? Checks whether the control is visible, in the expected location, and stands out from competing elements.</statement>
        <rationale>Visibility failures are distinct from labeling failures. An action can be correctly labeled but invisible because it is below the fold, de-emphasized, or surrounded by too many competing options. Common failures: action is below the fold or requires scrolling the user will not do; control does not look interactive (no visual affordance); too many competing options make the correct one non-salient.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Q3: Will the user associate the action with the effect? Checks whether the label matches the user's mental model, icon is recognizable, and location is consistent with conventions.</statement>
        <rationale>Labels are interpreted through the user's existing vocabulary, not the team's internal terminology. Domain jargon and feature names that the team uses daily are opaque to first-time users. Common failures: jargon in labels (internal product terminology, technical terms); ambiguous icons without labels; action placed where the user's mental model does not expect it.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Q4: Will the user see that progress is being made? Checks whether there is feedback after the action, UI state changes visibly, and success is communicated. Requires the post-action screen, not just the pre-action screen.</statement>
        <rationale>Without feedback, users repeat actions or abandon the task. Missing loading indicators, silent failures, and unchanged UI states after successful actions all produce the same user behavior: uncertainty leading to abandonment. Common failures: no loading indicator for async operations; page looks identical before and after a successful action; error message not displayed or not visible.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="framework-vs-heuristic-evaluation">
      <p>Cognitive walkthrough focuses on task completion by a new user with step-by-step task analysis and four specific questions per step. It is best for learnability and onboarding. Heuristic evaluation focuses on broad usability principles with expert review against 10 heuristics, best for general usability issues including efficiency for expert users. Use both: they catch different issue classes. Pair cog walk for learnability with heuristic evaluation for efficiency.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="worked-examples">
      <example type="good" title="Sign-Up Flow Step Evaluation">
        <note>Step: Click "Get Started" button. Persona: first-time user, no prior experience with the product.</note>
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
Q1: Will try to achieve right effect? YES
  Evidence: Clear value proposition above button establishes goal.

Q2: Will notice correct action available? PARTIAL
  Evidence: Button is visible but competes with "Sign In" at equal visual weight.

Q3: Will associate action with effect? NO
  Evidence: "Get Started" is ambiguous — could mean sign up, take a demo, or browse.

Q4: Will see progress? YES
  Evidence: Clicking navigates to registration form — clear state change.

Issue: Q3 failure — "Get Started" label does not communicate sign-up intent.
Fix: Change label to "Create Free Account" — removes ambiguity, communicates both action and cost.
        ]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="File Upload Step Evaluation">
        <note>Step: Drag file to upload zone. Persona: first-time user familiar with desktop file management.</note>
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
Q1: Will try to achieve right effect? PARTIAL
  Evidence: Users familiar with drag-drop will attempt; users who expect a browse button
  will look for it first and may not discover the drag zone.

Q2: Will notice correct action available? YES
  Evidence: Large, centered drop zone is visible and prominent.

Q3: Will associate action with effect? YES
  Evidence: Drop zone icon and "Drag files here" label clearly communicate the interaction.

Q4: Will see progress? NO
  Evidence: No upload progress indicator; no filename displayed during upload;
  page appears unchanged while upload runs.

Issue: Q4 failure — no feedback during file upload creates uncertainty and abandonment risk.
Fix: Add progress bar showing percentage and filename. Display "Uploading..." state
immediately on file drop before server confirmation.
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <rule>
        <statement>Treat each task-step as a self-contained unit: feed the agent (a) the persona description, (b) a screenshot of the current screen, (c) the intended next action. The agent answers Q1-Q4 with Yes/No/Partial plus evidence and a one-line fix. Run one screen at a time to keep context focused. A second meta-reviewer agent then ranks issues by severity and produces the summary report. Keep a human checkpoint before fixes are filed as tickets — agents over-flag minor wording.</statement>
        <rationale>Isolating steps prevents theme contamination; evaluating multi-step context causes earlier findings to bias later ones. Stateless per-step evaluation produces independent findings that can be merged without bias.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Agent Prompt Template for One-Step Evaluation">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
You are evaluating ONE step of a user task using the Cognitive Walkthrough method.

Persona: <<<one-paragraph first-time user persona>>>
Goal: <<<task goal>>>
Step <N> action: <<<exact intended action>>>
Screen: <attached image>

Answer ONLY in JSON:
{q1:{ans:"yes|no|partial", evidence:""},
 q2:{ans:"yes|no|partial", evidence:""},
 q3:{ans:"yes|no|partial", evidence:""},
 q4:{ans:"yes|no|partial", evidence:""},
 suggested_fix:""}.
For each "no" or "partial", evidence MUST quote a visible UI element
or explicitly state what is missing.
Do not assume capabilities the persona lacks.
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="antipatterns-and-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Evaluating the interface as an experienced user or product expert instead of as a first-time user.</description>
        <reason>Teams know the intended flow, terminology, and visual hierarchy intimately. This knowledge makes Q2 and Q3 failures invisible — controls that experts instantly recognize are opaque to first-time users with different vocabularies and mental models. Define a concrete first-time user persona with specific tech-savviness level, prior tools used, and absence of product knowledge. Inject this persona into every evaluation prompt and forbid the evaluator from assuming capabilities the persona lacks.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Evaluating only the steps that seem complex or where problems are anticipated, skipping steps the team assumes are obvious.</description>
        <reason>The steps a team assumes are obvious are precisely where first-time users fail — because the team's assumption of obviousness reflects expert familiarity, not user learnability. Skipping these steps misses high-value findings systematically.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Recording only "No" and "Partial" answers and not documenting steps where all four questions receive "Yes".</description>
        <reason>Positive findings identify what works and must not be changed. Without a record of positive Q1-Q4 answers, subsequent redesigns inadvertently remove successful elements while fixing failed ones.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Documenting issues as general observations ("the button is confusing") without citing the specific UI element and which question it fails.</description>
        <reason>Vague issues cannot be acted on. Every issue must cite: the step number, the specific UI element (quoted text or described element), the question it fails (Q1/Q2/Q3/Q4), and a concrete one-line fix suggestion. Structured issue format makes walkthroughs actionable.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Documenting findings without suggesting how to fix them, leaving interpretation entirely to the development team.</description>
        <reason>Findings without fixes get deprioritized because the team must first understand the issue deeply enough to devise a solution. Walkthrough findings with concrete fixes get resolved in the next sprint; findings without fixes get deferred.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Vision-LLMs over-recognize standard patterns ("That hamburger menu is obvious").</description>
        <reason>Inject the persona's tech-savviness explicitly and forbid assumptions. Agents conflate Q1 (motivation) with Q2 (visibility) — separate prompts per question reduce contamination.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Q4 needs the next screen too; static screenshots can't show absence of feedback.</description>
        <reason>Capture before+after pairs or animated GIFs. A locale mismatch where a Ukrainian-speaking persona walks an English-only UI fails Q3 by default — do not let the agent pretend it does not.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Severity inflation: agents tend to rank everything Medium.</description>
        <reason>Force a forced ranking: top 3 issues only at High; rest must be Medium or Low. Prototype screenshots may contain real names/emails in placeholder data — scrub before any vision call to a third-party API.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <rule>
        <statement>Persona must be concrete: name, age, prior tools used, first-time flag. Vague personas cause vague Q3 answers.</statement>
        <rationale>Concrete personas prevent drift toward expert mental models and focus evaluation on the actual target audience's knowledge gaps.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Always capture the screen before the action, not after. Q1-Q3 are about decision-making, Q4 alone is about post-action feedback.</statement>
        <rationale>Pre-action screenshots show the UI state where the user makes the decision to act; post-action screenshots alone cannot evaluate whether the pre-action UI was clear enough to motivate the action.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Keep the codebook tight: Yes / No / Partial — no free-text answers for the four questions. Free text goes in evidence.</statement>
        <rationale>Structured answers prevent vague responses and make findings comparable across multiple evaluators or steps.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Pair the walk with a heuristic evaluation pass; they catch different issue classes (learnability vs efficiency).</statement>
        <rationale>Cognitive walkthrough focuses on first-use learnability; heuristic evaluation catches expert-use efficiency and broad usability principles.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Re-run after each fix; cog walk is cheap, regression coverage matters.</statement>
        <rationale>Each fix may introduce new Q1-Q4 failures in downstream steps. Re-running is inexpensive relative to moderated testing and catches regressions early.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/walk.py" purpose="Playwright harness: drives browser, captures per-step screenshots, emits step JSON for evaluator agent"/>
    </templates>

